  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite the absence of online mentions or citations, \"The Point of Philosophy\" by Peter Lang Verlag is positioned as a pedagogical anchor, having been cited in one instance and held by four libraries, indicating a foundational role in academic discussions on its themes.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published in 2016, \"The Point of Philosophy\" serves as a noteworthy contribution to its discipline, even in the face of limited external engagement metrics such as citations and online discussions. The absence of digital mentions suggests a niche academic footprint, yet this does not diminish its presence in educational contexts.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The work is highlighted for its role as a pedagogical anchor, indicated by its holding in four libraries and being listed in one Open Teaching Learning platform. This suggests that while it has not yet gained wide popular attention, it has found some utility in formal educational settings, where it may contribute to structured learning about philosophical concepts.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Furthermore, the assessment of scholarly uptake indicates that the publication has received at least one citation. This reflects a degree of academic recognition within its field, positioning it as a potentially valuable resource for scholars and students alike who are exploring related philosophical discussions.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In summary, while \"The Point of Philosophy\" may not have extensive public or online discourse, its role in academic libraries and its citation demonstrate its foundational significance in philosophy education. Continued exploration of its themes could foster broader dialogue and scholarly engagement in the future.</p>",
